The paper deals with a geometric problem of identifying points in the plane using disks, which falls under computational geometry (cs.CG). The use of tight lower and upper bounds on the number of disks needed suggests a combinatorial approach, making categories such as discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) likely. The mention of complexity issues and NP-completeness points towards computational complexity (cs.CC) as a possible category. Finally, the use of linear-time algorithms suggests graph theory (cs.GT) as another possible category.
